    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 112, n. <citedRange>91</citedRange>, fig. 47</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.203</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>024700</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#beschi1970"/>, p. <citedRange>204</citedRange> (date of the base)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>139</citedRange> (probable provenance)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.85</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-66103"><name nymRef="#Φίλων">Φίλων</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65705"><name nymRef="#Σωσίας" type="patronymic">Σωσία</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Philon fils de Sôsias.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Philon son of Sosias.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Philon figlio di Sosias.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Philon might be brother of Teleso (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr024800</ref>): both bases, published together and very similar,
                    should come from the same tomb.</p>
                <p>The Thorns' probable attribution to the North Necropolis is due to the fact that the Italian archaeologists before World War II were mainly interested 
                    in this one.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
